1. What Destructuring Means

Definition:
Destructuring is a convenient way of extracting values from arrays or objects into individual variables.
Instead of accessing properties or elements repeatedly, you can “unpack” them directly.Example:
Without destructuring:

const person = { name: "Alice", age: 25 };
const name = person.name;
const age = person.age;

With destructuring:

const { name, age } = person;

2. Destructuring Arrays

Basic Syntax:

const numbers = [1, 2, 3];
const [first, second] = numbers;
console.log(first, second); // 1 2

Skipping items:

const [,, third] = numbers;
console.log(third); // 3

3. Destructuring Objects

Basic Syntax:

const user = { username: "bob123", email: "bob@example.com" };
const { username, email } = user;
console.log(username, email);

Renaming variables:

const { username: userName, email: userEmail } = user;

Nested objects:

const user = { name: "Alice", address: { city: "NY", zip: 10001 } };
const { address: { city, zip } } = user;


4. Default Values

Destructuring allows default values if a property/element is undefined.

Array example:

const numbers = [10];
const [a, b = 20] = numbers;
console.log(a, b); // 10 20

Object example:

const options = { size: "M" };
const { size, color = "blue" } = options;
console.log(size, color); // M blue


5. Benefits of Destructuring
Less repetitive code: No need to repeatedly write obj.property or arr[index].
Clearer intent: It’s obvious which variables you’re extracting.
Works with function parameters: You can destructure directly in function arguments.

Example (before vs after):
Before:

function greet(user) {
  const name = user.name;
  const age = user.age;
  console.log(`Hello ${name}, you are ${age}`);
}

After:

function greet({ name, age }) {
  console.log(`Hello ${name}, you are ${age}`);
}

